 Latinx Studies masterfully sheds light on the diversity and complexity of the everyday lives of Latinx populations, the political economic structures that shape enduring racialization and cultural stereotyping, and the continuing efforts to carve out new lives as diasporic, transnational, global, and colonial subjects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHispanic Americans. 0aLatin AmericanszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAddiction.  aAesthetics.  aAfro-Cuban.  aAfro-Latinidad.  aAfro-Latinos.  aAfro-Mexico.  aAfroLatinidad.  aAfroLatinx Studies.  aAnti-black bias.  aArgentina.  aArgentine.  aArt.  aBarrio.  aBelonging.  aBlack Indigeneity.  aBorderlands.  aBuilt environment.  aCalifornia.  aCensus.  aCentral America.  aCentral American Studies.  aCentral American-American.  aChicago.  aChicano Park.  aChicanx studies.  aChonga.  aChristianity.  aCitizenship.  aCivil rights law.  aColombia.  aColonialism.  aComparative Ethnic studies.  aCriminalization.  aCritical University Studies.  aCuban America.  aDeportation.  aDeviancy.  aDiaspora.  aDigital Activism.  aDiscrimination.  aDispossession.  aDominican Republic.  aDrag.  aEducation.  aEl Barrio.  aEl Salvador.  aEthnic labels.  aEthnography.  aFamilies.  aFamily dispersions.  aFamily separation.  aFamily.  aFarmworkers.  aFemininity.  aGarifuna New Yorkers.  aGender and Sexual Non-normativity.  aGender.  aGenetics.  aGuatemala.  aGuillermo Alvarez Guedes.  aHealth.  aHomeless.  aHonduras.  aHousing.  aHumanistic social sciences.  aHurricanes.  aIdentity.  aImmigrants.  aImmigration regimes.  aImmigration.  aImperialism.  aIndigenous.  aInheritance.  